(What This Topic Means) Tj
T*
(Indirect speech reports what was said without repeating the exact words. In English,) Tj
T*
(students do better when they understand not only the definition of Indirect Speech, but) Tj
T*
(also the language, symbols, and patterns that appear whenever this topic is tested.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Core Explanation) Tj
T*
(The central focus in Indirect Speech is reported-speech changes in tense, pronouns, and) Tj
T*
(time words. A strong explanation should show the idea clearly, connect it to prior) Tj
T*
(knowledge, and then walk through the method students are expected to use whenever they) Tj
T*
(meet this topic in classwork or examination questions.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Understanding) Tj
T*
(A good classroom illustration for Indirect Speech is changing a direct sentence into) Tj
T*
(reported speech. When students can talk through that kind of example slowly and) Tj
T*
(correctly, they usually find it much easier to transfer the same reasoning to new) Tj
T*
(questions.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Why Students Find It Difficult) Tj
T*
(One frequent problem in Indirect Speech is keeping original tense and pronouns) Tj
T*
(unchanged. Students also struggle when they try to memorize final answers without) Tj
T*
(understanding the steps that make the answer valid. Clear explanations, careful) Tj
T*
(checking, and repeated guided practice reduce this difficulty.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Real Learning Application) Tj
T*
